snippet.textDisplay:
Whether or not Peter or Madison would have worked out, his parents should have never been given a chance to speak on this show. They never had parents on ATFR and they only put them on now because Barb is a reality-tv producer’s dream. They had a camera positioned on her from the beginning and every chance they had they put her on screen to see if she’d react and she gave them that and more.
Not only did she embarrass Madison, someone they barely knew and decided to hate after falling in love with Hannah Ann (another girl they barely knew), they embarrassed their son and made him look like a spineless fool who can’t make decisions for himself, and they also embarrassed themselves. She showed her true self: a narcissistic manipulator, and her husband is now seen as her meek submissive partner.
Madison is lucky so could get out when she did. There will be ramifications between Peter and his family. And with the way his mother holds grudges (you’re still sour that you had to wait 3 hours to meet her? Even though that was probably out of her control?), it could be a long time before things go back to normal (if at all).

snippet.textDisplay: Madison should've told Peter earlier that she was saving herself for marriage. Madison seems unapologetic and she never seems to take any accountability for anything. What viewers are forgetting is that Peter gave his heart to Hannah and Hannah's wasn't able to reciprocate the same feelings back. Naturally the parents don't want the same thing to happen to their son again if they seeing a similar pattern in Madison. Peter told his parents that Madison never told him that she loves him. Naturally, the parents are trying to protect him from giving his love to someone who is not able reciprocating the love in the same level. Madison was able to go through this journey while protecting her heart while Peter and the last few girls gave themselves entirely to the process. Madison could've apologized to the parents for making them wait but she didn't and to me that shows the side of Madison that seems to a theme with her...she always think she's perfect, pure, right all the time, and never without fault.
